COLOMBIA GeoRED Project

Data Summary

This is a use case to offer some insight to what a user can do with the limited information that they may have to determine if a GNSS station is a viable tide gauge.

In this scenario, we have been asked to evaluate the viablity of a GNSS station to provide tidal measurements given rinex data with no further information.

This type of scenario might be useful for:

  • someone asked to process rinex data not held in public archives
  • for users that are asked to assess data from a temporary installation that would inform whether a permanent installation would support reflection height retrieval.

# This is only for these use cases - you can set pltscreen=True in quicklook to print these plots as well
def pretty_plots(station, values, frequency, metrics=None):
    # plotting the quicklook graph periodograms
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=2, nrows=2, figsize=(12,10), sharex=True)
    fig.suptitle(f'QuickLook: {station},{frequency}', size=16)

    quadrants = ['NW', 'NE', 'SW', 'SE']
    quadrant_labels = ['Northwest','Northeast', 'Southwest', 'Southeast']

    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat):
        quad = quadrants[i]
        for fail_satellite in values[f'f{quad}']:
            g = sns.lineplot(x=values[f'f{quad}'][fail_satellite][0],
                             y=values[f'f{quad}'][fail_satellite][1],
                             ax=ax, color='lightgrey')
        for satellite in values[quad]:
            g = sns.lineplot(x=values[quad][satellite][0],
                             y=values[quad][satellite][1],
                             ax=ax, lw=3)
        g.set_title(quadrant_labels[i])
        g.set_ylabel('volts/volts')
        g.set_xlabel('reflector height (m)')

    if metrics:
        success, fail = gnssrefl_helpers.quicklook_metrics(metrics)
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=1, nrows=3, figsize=(10,7), sharex=True)
        fig.suptitle(f'QuickLook Retrieval Metrics: {station}, {frequency}', size=16)

        for i, ax in enumerate(axes):
            g = sns.scatterplot(x='Azimuth',y=fail.columns[i+1], s=100, data=fail, ax=ax, color='grey', label='bad', alpha=.5)
            g = sns.scatterplot(x='Azimuth',y=success.columns[i+1], s=100, data=success, ax=ax, label='good')
            
        axes[0].legend(loc='upper right')
        axes[1].axhline(3, linestyle='--', color='black')
        axes[2].axhline(7, linestyle='--', color='black')

        avg_rh = np.mean(success['Reflector Height'])
        print(f'Average reflector height value: {avg_rh:.1f}')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Lets begin: the RINEX file(s)

First, we review the recommendations from the source repo on bringing your own files to process.

What if you want to analyze your own data?

Put your RINEX 2.11 files in the directory where you are going to run the code. They must have SNR data in them (S1, S2, etc) and have the receiver coordinates in the >header. The files should be named as follows:

  • lowercase
  • station name (4 characters) followed by day of year (3 characters) then 0.yyo where yy is >the two character year.
  • Example: algo0500.21o where station name is algo on day of year 50 from the year 2021

rinex2snr algo 2021 50 -nolook True

Our file (images/cccp0840.22o) is named correctly and we'll move it from /images/ to the current directory.

Let's take a look at the file with any text editor or in a jupyter browser window.

We identify some key parameters from the RINEX header:

  • LOCATION: We will use the header coordinates for our site evaluation and processing.
  • SIGNALS: The header informs us that the RINEX is formatted to include our signals of interest: carrier to noise ratios S(1-8)
  • CONSTELLATIONS: Under the list of satellites included, we can see that two satellite systems are tracked, GPS (GXX) and GLONASS (RXX)

First location assessment: GNSS Reflection Zone app

Now we can use the reflection zone part of the web app using the coordinates from the header to map fresnel zones of our surface reflections (the effective sampling area):

  • Latitude 1.82
  • Longitude -78.729
  • Height (m) 21.3

This looks very promising!

The low elevation fresnel zones (yellow ellipse) are almost entirely on water.
Without site photos, we do not know what local antenna environment effects might exist, such as additional reflectors or obstructions (walls, buildings) adjacent to the antenna, but we have good reason to continue with our investigation at this point.

While reflections on water exist nearly 360 degrees around, we identify the trees and structures on shore that might block the lowest elevation signals.

We also return an estimated reflection height relative to MSL of 7 meters; remember this.

We continue with the rinex processing with the rinex2snr utility to extract SNR and estimate satellite azimuth and elevations.

quickLook()

Now we run the quicklook utility using all of its default settings. quickLook() is exactly what its name implies: a function to rapidly visualize the reflected signals from snr files.

In[6]:
values, metrics = quicklook(station, year, doy=doy, pltscreen=False)
pretty_plots(station, values, 'GPS L1', metrics)

minimum elevation angle (degrees) for this dataset:  0.0184
Average reflector height value: 2.9

Using the default settings with quicklook, we might think it is not a very useful site. There are a few "good" retrievals, but they are fairly intermittent w.r.t. azimuth.

Don't give up yet though, quickLook is designed to get you results quickly, but in doing so has to make many assumptions about its defaults that are not universal:

  • In the top plot, our first red flag is that the reflector heights end at 6m; our antenna is positioned 7m above MSL.

  • We may want to modify the default elevation masks.

Let's see what the defaults are set to by adding a question mark to the function and running that cell.

We will lower the elevation mask to 5 to 13 degrees (Larson et al., 2017) and increase our height window to include our MSL reflector height estimate of 7m.

In[8]:
values, metrics = quicklook(station, year, doy=doy,
                                         e1=5, e2=13, h1=3, h2=10, fr=20, pltscreen=False)

pretty_plots(station, values, 'GPS L1', metrics)

minimum elevation angle (degrees) for this dataset:  0.0184
Average reflector height value: 5.2

Much better: Now we can roughly see that the acceptable azimuths will fall ~130 to 230 degrees. A peak to noise ratio of 3 works pretty well as a theshold.

The Lomb Scargle periodograms show the retrievals in reflector height space (derived from the snr beat frequency). As a reminder, we retrieve these heights, HR, by modeling SNR as: $$SNR(e)=A(e)\sin(\frac{4\pi H_{R}}{\lambda}\sin(e) + \phi)$$

Where e is satellite evelation angle wrt the horizon, A(e) is the signal amplitude as a function of elevation, lamda is the gnss signal wavelength, phi is the phase offset, and HR is the relative height of the antenna phase center above the reflection surface. For more discussion about reflector heights, see Roesler & Larson (2017)

In our case, it is evident that the northeast is null for low elevation water reflections: this is likely from the trees on shore obscuring these low elevation signals. The northwest has very few as well, likely again from shoreline obstructions.

Another feature that stands out is the gap in retrievals to the south. This is a function of the GPS orbital parameters and our location. We might have noticed this in the refl zones plotting tool fresnel zones. The Trimble planning tool is another tool for a quick visualization. This is unavoidable for our case here, but a useful consideration for future site planning.

We can also look at modern L2C signals (-fr=20).

These are not available for all satellites (satellites broadcasting this signal changes with time, mostly additive) but offer improved, higher gain SNR.

Now we also get retrievals in southern azimuths (150-200 deg).

Multi constellation tracking has many application benefits-- For our application it adds retrievals in addition to satellite geometry diversity.

Analyze the Data

Next we will set up our analysis for the three days of data we've been provided.

Our workflow is as follows:

  1. rinex2snr() Translates the files to snr files
  2. make_json_input() Builds a configuration file for reflectometery processing parameters
  3. gnssir() Estimates reflection heights (RH) that meet QC metrics
  4. subdaily() Concatenates RH timeseries, removes outliers, computes RH dot correction and plots timeseries

We need to select azimuth ranges that include useful reflections.

We can edit the json file manually using a text editor, or use the cell below to help edit the json file.

We cannot set azimuth ranges > 100 degrees. This limit is built into gnssrefl to ensure rising and setting arcs reflector heights are estimated independently.

Given the results from quickLook, combined with our Google earth image, we will constrain our azimuth range from 75-230.

We are also going to edit out the Galileo and Beidou signals since they are not included in these rinex files.

In[14]:
# Now lets edit the json file
with open(json_file, "r") as myfile:
    file = json.load(myfile)
    
# Here is where we can 'hand edit' values in the json file
# lets edit the azimuths. We set these values by looking at the metrics qc plot above
file['azval'] = [70,150,150,230]
file['freqs'] = [1,20,5,101,102]
os.remove(json_file)

with open(json_file, 'w') as f:
    json.dump(file, f, indent=4)
    
# now lets view it again and note the difference
with open(json_file, "r") as myfile:
    file = json.load(myfile)

subdaily()

This the function that concatenates the qc'ed reflection heights output from gnssir() and makes an effort to apply an RH Dot correction to account for change in reflector height over the individual processed arc.

INVSNR

The library for retrieving reflector heights from inverse modeling (Strandberg et al., 2016) is not yet included in the notebook implementation, but is well documented in a readme for running from the command line.

invsnr_input cccp 3 10 5 13 -lat 1.82 -lon -78.729 -height 21.333 -a1 75 -a2 230

invsnr cccp 2022 84 L1+L2+L5 -doy_end 86
